{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἄπιος</b>, η, ον, <br /> <br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <b>far away, far off, distant,</b> τηλόθεν ἐξ ἀπίης γαίης[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.270, 3.49, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 16.18, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1685. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> Ἄπιος, α, ον, <b>Apian,</b> i.e. <b>Peloponnesian,</b> said (in this sense) to be derived from Ἆπις, Apis, a mythical king of Argos, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 260, compare 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 2.5.7\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; Ἀπία γῆ, Ἀπία χθών, or Ἀπία alone, <b>the Peloponnese,</b> especially <b>Argolis,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 256, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1303, 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 14.650b, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; compareἈπίς probably in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1564\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]. [The former word has ᾰ, the latter ; yet [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1685 uses signification 1\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] with ᾱ, and later <i>Epic dialect</i> Poets have <i>signification</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11 with ᾰ,compare 3rd c.BC: Rhianus Epicus 13.] (Commonly derived from ἀπό, as ἀντίος\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] from ἀντ; and [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus explanation ἐξ ἀπίης γαίης by ἀλλοτρίας ἢ ξένης ἢ μακρὰν οὔσης,compare 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 8.6.9.)\">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G6412","accentedUnicode":"ἄπιος","shortDef":"pear tree","mediumDef":"pear tree, distant","stepGloss":"pear tree","stepTransliteration":"apios","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}